{"cursor":"96121","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\" by John William Waterhouse]]\n\n'Magic' is the art of producing a desired effect or result through the use of\nincantation, ceremony, ritual, the casting of spells or various other techniques\nthat presumably assure human control of supernatural agencies or the forces of\nnature. magic. Dictionary.com. Dictionary.com Unabridged. Random House, Inc.\nhttp://dictionary.reference.com/browse/magic (accessed: May 24, 2012).\nMagic has been practiced in many cultures, and utilizes ways of understanding,\nexperiencing and influencing the world somewhat akin to those offered by\nreligion, though it is sometimes regarded as more focused on achieving results\nthan religious worship. Mauss, Tambiah, Malinowski (see below);  Magic\nis often viewed with suspicion by the wider community, and is commonly practiced\nin isolation and secrecy. Mauss, Marcel\n(1972) A General Theory of Magic (R. Brain, Trans.). New York: Norton Library.\n(Original work published 1903). p. 24\n\nModern Western magicians generally state magic's primary purpose to be personal\nspiritual growth. Cicero, Chic & Sandra Tabatha () The Essential Golden\nDawn: An Introduction to High Magic. pp. 87â9. Regardie, Israel (2001) The Tree\nof Life: An Illustrated Study of Magic, St. Paul, Minnesota: Llewellyn, p. 17.\nCrowley, Aleister Magic Without Tears Ch. 83. Modern perspectives on the\ntheory of magic broadly follow two major views. The first sees magic as a result\nof a universal sympathy within the universe, where if something is done here a\nresult happens somewhere else. The other view sees magic as a collaboration with\nspirits who cause the effect.\n","linknr":1176,"url":"Magic_(paranormal)","recorded":1362484765,"links":97,"instances":["paranormal","folk_magic","magic","sorcery","video_game","mythology","region","aleister_crowley","wiccan","folk_magic","arts","illusion","religion","contemporary","paranormal","new_thought","physics